# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: level-of-detail
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:level-of-detail/clipmap] In computer graphics, **clipmapping** is a method of clipping a mipmap to a subset of data pertinent to the geometry being displayed.
[src:level-of-detail/clipmap] The technique was introduced by Christopher C.
[src:level-of-detail/clipmap] Jones as a "virtual mipmap" for caching arbitrarily large textures in finite physical memory for real-time rendering.
[src:level-of-detail/clipmap] This is useful for loading as little data as possible when memory is limited, such as on a graphics processing unit.
[src:level-of-detail/clipmap] For terrain rendering, the idea was adapted into geometry clipmaps, which use nested regular grids centered on the viewer and update them incrementally as the viewpoint moves.
[src:level-of-detail/clipmap] The technique is used for LODing in NVIDIA’s implementation of voxel cone tracing.
[src:level-of-detail/clipmap] The high-resolution levels of the mipmapped scene representation are clipped to a region near the camera, while lower resolution levels are clipped further away.
[src:level-of-detail/clipmap] MegaTexture is a clipmap implementation developed by id Software.
[src:level-of-detail/clipmap] It was introduced in their id Tech 4 engine and also appeared in id Tech 5 and id Tech 6 before being removed in id Tech 7.
[src:level-of-detail/clipmap] MegaTexture is a texture allocation technique that uses a single, extremely large texture rather than repeating multiple smaller textures.
[src:level-of-detail/clipmap] It is also featured in Splash Damage's game *Enemy Territory: Quake Wars*, and was developed by id Software former technical director John Carmack.
[src:level-of-detail/clipmap] MegaTexture employs a single large texture space for static terrain.
[src:level-of-detail/clipmap] The texture is stored on removable media or a computer's hard drive and streamed as needed, allowing large amounts of detail and variation over a large area with comparatively little RAM usage.
[src:level-of-detail/clipmap] Depending on the pixel resolution per square meter, covering a large area could require several gigabytes of memory.
[src:level-of-detail/clipmap] However, RAM is also filled by the rest of the game and the underlying operating system, limiting the amount available for texturing.
[src:level-of-detail/clipmap] As the player moves around the game, different sections of the MegaTexture are loaded into memory.
[src:level-of-detail/clipmap] They are then scaled to the correct size and applied to the 3D models of the terrain.
[src:level-of-detail/clipmap] Id has presented a more advanced technique that builds upon the MegaTexture idea and virtualizes both the geometry and the textures to obtain unique geometry down to the equivalent of the texel: the sparse voxel octree (SVO).
[src:level-of-detail/clipmap] It works by raycasting the geometry represented by voxels (instead of triangles) stored in an octree.
[src:level-of-detail/clipmap] The geometric detail that can be obtained using this method is nearly infinite, which removes the need for faking 3-dimensional details with techniques such as normal mapping.
[src:level-of-detail/clipmap] Despite that most voxel rendering tests use very large amounts of memory (up to several GB), Jon Olick of id Software claimed the technology is able to compress such SVO to 1.15 bits per voxel of position data.
[src:level-of-detail/clipmap] Unlike clipmaps, which clip each mip level around a viewpoint-dependent clipcenter and therefore work best for terrain, virtual texturing preprocesses texture data into equally sized tiles that can be streamed for arbitrary textured geometry.
[src:level-of-detail/clipmap] *Rage*, powered by the id Tech 5 engine, uses a more advanced technique called virtual texturing.
[src:level-of-detail/clipmap] Textures can measure up to 128000×128000 pixels and are also used for in-game models and sprites, etc. and not just the terrain.
[src:level-of-detail/impostor-computer-graphics] In computer graphics, a **sprite** is a two-dimensional bitmap that is integrated into a larger scene, most often in a 2D video game.
[src:level-of-detail/impostor-computer-graphics] Originally, the term *sprite* referred to fixed-sized objects composited together, by hardware, with a background.
[src:level-of-detail/impostor-computer-graphics] Use of the term has since become more general.
[src:level-of-detail/impostor-computer-graphics] Hardware varies in the number of sprites supported, the size and colors of each sprite, and special effects such as scaling or reporting pixel-precise overlap.
[src:level-of-detail/impostor-computer-graphics] Hardware composition of sprites occurs as each scan line is prepared for the video output device, such as a cathode-ray tube, without involvement of the main CPU and without the need for a full-screen frame buffer.
[src:level-of-detail/impostor-computer-graphics] Sprites can be positioned or altered by setting attributes used during the hardware composition process.
[src:level-of-detail/impostor-computer-graphics] The number of sprites which can be displayed per scan line is often lower than the total number of sprites a system supports.
[src:level-of-detail/impostor-computer-graphics] For example, the Texas Instruments TMS9918 chip supports 32 sprites, but only four can appear on the same scan line.
[src:level-of-detail/impostor-computer-graphics] The CPUs in modern computers, video game consoles, and mobile devices are fast enough that bitmaps can be drawn into a frame buffer without special hardware assistance.
[src:level-of-detail/impostor-computer-graphics] Beyond that, GPUs can render vast numbers of scaled, rotated, anti-aliased, partially translucent, very high resolution images in parallel with the CPU.
[src:level-of-detail/impostor-computer-graphics] According to Karl Guttag, one of two engineers for the 1979 Texas Instruments TMS9918 video display processor, this use of the word *sprite* came from David Ackley, a manager at TI.
[src:level-of-detail/impostor-computer-graphics] It was also used by Danny Hillis at Texas Instruments in the late 1970s.
[src:level-of-detail/impostor-computer-graphics] The term was derived from the fact that sprites "float" on top of the background image without overwriting it, much like a ghost or mythological sprite.
[src:level-of-detail/impostor-computer-graphics] The use of sprites originated with arcade video games.
[src:level-of-detail/impostor-computer-graphics] Nolan Bushnell came up with the original concept when he developed the first arcade video game, *Computer Space* (1971).
[src:level-of-detail/impostor-computer-graphics] Technical limitations made it difficult to adapt the early mainframe game *Spacewar!* (1962), which performed an entire screen refresh for every little movement, so he came up with a solution to the problem: controlling each individual game element with a dedicated transistor.
[src:level-of-detail/impostor-computer-graphics] The rockets were essentially hardwired bitmaps that moved around the screen independently of the background, an important innovation for producing screen images more efficiently and providing the basis for sprite graphics.
[src:level-of-detail/impostor-computer-graphics] The earliest video games to represent player characters as human player sprites were arcade sports video games, beginning with Taito's *TV Basketball*, released in April 1974 and licensed to Midway Manufacturing for release in North America.
[src:level-of-detail/impostor-computer-graphics] Designed by Tomohiro Nishikado, he wanted to move beyond simple *Pong*-style rectangles to character graphics, by rearranging the rectangle shapes into objects that look like basketball players and basketball hoops.
[src:level-of-detail/impostor-computer-graphics] Ramtek released another sports video game in October 1974, *Baseball*, which similarly displayed human-like characters.
[src:level-of-detail/impostor-computer-graphics] The Namco Galaxian arcade system board, for the 1979 arcade game *Galaxian*, displays animated, multi-colored sprites over a scrolling background.
[src:level-of-detail/impostor-computer-graphics] It became the basis for Nintendo's *Radar Scope* and *Donkey Kong* arcade hardware and home consoles such as the Nintendo Entertainment System.
[src:level-of-detail/impostor-computer-graphics] According to Steve Golson from General Computer Corporation, the term "stamp" was used instead of "sprite" at the time.
[src:level-of-detail/impostor-computer-graphics] Signetics devised the first chips capable of generating sprite graphics (referred to as *objects* by Signetics) for home systems.
[src:level-of-detail/impostor-computer-graphics] The Signetics 2636 video processors were first used in the 1978 1292 Advanced Programmable Video System and later in the 1979 Elektor TV Games Computer.
[src:level-of-detail/impostor-computer-graphics] The Atari VCS, released in 1977, has a hardware sprite implementation where five graphical objects can be moved independently of the game playfield.
[src:level-of-detail/impostor-computer-graphics] The term *sprite* was not in use at the time.
[src:level-of-detail/impostor-computer-graphics] The VCS's sprites are called *movable objects* in the programming manual, further identified as two *players*, two *missiles*, and one *ball*.
[src:level-of-detail/impostor-computer-graphics] These each consist of a single row of pixels that are displayed on a scan line.
[src:level-of-detail/impostor-computer-graphics] To produce a two-dimensional shape, the sprite's single-row bitmap is altered by software from one scan line to the next.
[src:level-of-detail/impostor-computer-graphics] The 1979 Atari 400 and 800 home computers have similar, but more elaborate, circuitry capable of moving eight single-color objects per scan line: four 8-bit wide *players* and four 2-bit wide *missiles*.
[src:level-of-detail/impostor-computer-graphics] Each is the full height of the display—a long, thin strip.
[src:level-of-detail/impostor-computer-graphics] DMA from a table in memory automatically sets the graphics pattern registers for each scan line.
[src:level-of-detail/impostor-computer-graphics] Hardware registers control the horizontal position of each player and missile.
[src:level-of-detail/impostor-computer-graphics] Vertical motion is achieved by moving the bitmap data within a player or missile's strip.
[src:level-of-detail/impostor-computer-graphics] The feature was called *player/missile graphics* by Atari.
[src:level-of-detail/impostor-computer-graphics] Texas Instruments developed the TMS9918 chip with sprite support for its 1979 TI-99/4 home computer.
[src:level-of-detail/impostor-computer-graphics] An updated version is used in the 1981 TI-99/4A.
[src:level-of-detail/impostor-computer-graphics] Sprites remained popular with the rise of 2.5D games (those which recreate a 3D game space from a 2D map) in the late 1980s and early 1990s.
[src:level-of-detail/impostor-computer-graphics] A technique called billboarding allows 2.5D games to keep onscreen sprites rotated toward the player view at all times.
[src:level-of-detail/impostor-computer-graphics] Some 2.5D games, such as 1993's *Doom*, allow the same entity to be represented by different sprites depending on its rotation relative to the viewer, furthering the illusion of 3D.
[src:level-of-detail/impostor-computer-graphics] Fully 3D games usually present world objects as 3D models, but sprites are supported in some 3D game engines, such as GoldSrc and Unreal, and may be billboarded or locked to fixed orientations.
[src:level-of-detail/impostor-computer-graphics] Sprites remain useful for small details, particle effects, and other applications where the lack of a third dimension is not a major detriment.
[src:level-of-detail/impostor-computer-graphics] These are base hardware specs and do not include additional programming techniques, such as using raster interrupts to repurpose sprites mid-frame.
[src:level-of-detail/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] In computer graphics, **level of detail** (**LOD**) refers to the complexity of a 3D model representation.
[src:level-of-detail/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] LOD can be decreased as the model moves away from the viewer or according to other metrics such as object importance, viewpoint-relative speed or position.
[src:level-of-detail/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] LOD techniques increase the efficiency of rendering by decreasing the workload on graphics pipeline stages, usually vertex transformations.
[src:level-of-detail/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] The reduced visual quality of the model is often unnoticed because of the small effect on object appearance when distant or moving fast.
[src:level-of-detail/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] Although most of the time LOD is applied to geometry detail only, the basic concept can be generalized.
[src:level-of-detail/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] Recently, LOD techniques also included shader management to keep control of pixel complexity.
[src:level-of-detail/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] A form of level of detail management has been applied to texture maps for years, under the name of mipmapping, also providing higher rendering quality.
[src:level-of-detail/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] It is commonplace to say that "an object has been *LOD-ed*" when the object is simplified by the underlying *LOD-ing algorithm* as well as a 3D modeler manually creating LOD models.
[src:level-of-detail/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] The origin[1] of all the LOD algorithms for 3D computer graphics can be traced back to an article by James H.
[src:level-of-detail/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] Clark in the October 1976 issue of *Communications of the ACM*.
[src:level-of-detail/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] At the time, computers were monolithic and rare, and graphics were being driven by researchers.
[src:level-of-detail/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] The hardware itself was completely different, both architecturally and performance-wise.
[src:level-of-detail/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] As such, many differences could be observed with regard to today's algorithms but also many common points.
[src:level-of-detail/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] The original algorithm presented a much more generic approach to what will be discussed here.
[src:level-of-detail/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] After introducing some available algorithms for geometry management, it is stated that most fruitful gains came from *"...structuring the environments being rendered"*, allowing to exploit faster transformations and clipping operations.
[src:level-of-detail/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] The proposed algorithm envisions a tree data structure which encodes in its arcs both transformations and transitions to more detailed objects.
[src:level-of-detail/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] In this way, each node encodes an object and according to a fast heuristic, the tree is descended to the leaves which provide each object with more detail.
[src:level-of-detail/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] When a leaf is reached, other methods could be used when higher detail is needed, such as Catmull's recursive subdivision[2].
[src:level-of-detail/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] The paper then introduces clipping (not to be confused with culling although often similar), various considerations on the *graphical working set* and its impact on performance, interactions between the proposed algorithm and others to improve rendering speed.
[src:level-of-detail/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] Although the algorithm introduced above covers a whole range of level of detail management techniques, real world applications usually employ specialized methods tailored to the information being rendered.
[src:level-of-detail/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] The first method, **discrete level of detail** (**DLOD**), involves creating multiple, discrete versions of the original geometry with decreased levels of geometric detail.
[src:level-of-detail/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] At runtime, the full-detail models are substituted for the models with reduced detail as necessary.
[src:level-of-detail/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] Due to the discrete nature of the levels, there may be visual popping when one model is exchanged for another.
[src:level-of-detail/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] This may be mitigated by alpha blending or morphing between states during the transition.
[src:level-of-detail/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] The second method, **continuous level of detail** (**CLOD**), uses a structure which contains a continuously variable spectrum of geometric detail.
[src:level-of-detail/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] The structure can then be probed to smoothly choose the appropriate level of detail required for the situation.
[src:level-of-detail/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] A significant advantage of this technique is the ability to locally vary the detail; for instance, the side of a large object nearer to the view may be presented in high detail, while simultaneously reducing the detail on its distant side.
[src:level-of-detail/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] In both cases, LODs are chosen based on some heuristic which is used to judge how much detail is being lost by the reduction in detail, such as by evaluation of the LOD's geometric error relative to the full-detail model.
[src:level-of-detail/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] Objects are then displayed with the minimum amount of detail required to satisfy the heuristic, which is designed to minimize geometric detail as much as possible to maximize performance while maintaining an acceptable level of visual quality.
[src:level-of-detail/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] The basic concept of discrete LOD (DLOD) is to provide various models to represent the same object.
[src:level-of-detail/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] Obtaining those models requires an external algorithm which is often non-trivial and subject of many polygon reduction techniques.
[src:level-of-detail/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] Successive LOD-ing algorithms will simply assume those models are available.
[src:level-of-detail/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] DLOD algorithms are often used in performance-intensive applications with small data sets which can easily fit in memory.
[src:level-of-detail/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] Although out-of-core algorithms could be used, the information granularity is not well suited to this kind of application.
[src:level-of-detail/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] This kind of algorithm is usually easier to get working, providing both faster performance and lower CPU usage because of the few operations involved.
[src:level-of-detail/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] DLOD methods are often used for "stand-alone" moving objects, possibly including complex animation methods.
[src:level-of-detail/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] A different approach is used for geomipmapping,[3] a popular terrain rendering algorithm because this applies to terrain meshes which are both graphically and topologically different from "object" meshes.
[src:level-of-detail/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] Instead of computing an error and simplify the mesh according to this, geomipmapping takes a fixed reduction method, evaluates the error introduced and computes a distance at which the error is acceptable.
[src:level-of-detail/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] Although straightforward, the algorithm provides decent performance.
[src:level-of-detail/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] A discrete LOD approach would cache a certain number of models to be used at different distances.
[src:level-of-detail/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] Because the model can trivially be procedurally generated by its mathematical formulation, using a different number of sample points distributed on the surface is sufficient to generate the various models required.
[src:level-of-detail/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] To simulate a realistic transform bound scenario, an ad-hoc written application can be used.
[src:level-of-detail/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] The use of simple algorithms and minimum fragment operations ensures that CPU bounding does not occur.
[src:level-of-detail/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] Each frame, the program will compute each sphere's distance and choose a model from a pool according to this information.
[src:level-of-detail/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] To easily show the concept, the distance at which each model is used is hard coded in the source.
[src:level-of-detail/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] A more involved method would compute adequate models according to the usage distance chosen.
[src:level-of-detail/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] OpenGL is used for rendering due to its high efficiency in managing small batches, storing each model in a display list thus avoiding communication overheads.
[src:level-of-detail/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] Additional vertex load is given by applying two directional light sources ideally located infinitely far away.
[src:level-of-detail/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] The following table compares the performance of LOD aware rendering and a full detail (*brute force*) method.
[src:level-of-detail/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] Because hardware is geared towards large amounts of detail, rendering low polygon objects may score sub-optimal performances.
[src:level-of-detail/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] HLOD avoids the problem by grouping different objects together[4].
[src:level-of-detail/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] This allows for higher efficiency as well as taking advantage of proximity considerations.
[src:level-of-detail/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] LOD is especially useful in 3D video games.
[src:level-of-detail/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] Video game developers want to provide players with large worlds but are always constrained by hardware, frame rate and the real-time nature of video game graphics.
[src:level-of-detail/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] With the advent of 3D games in the 1990s, a lot of video games simply did not render distant structures or objects.
[src:level-of-detail/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] Only nearby objects would be rendered and more distant parts would gradually fade, essentially implementing distance fog.
[src:level-of-detail/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] Video games using LOD rendering avoid this fog effect and can render larger areas.
[src:level-of-detail/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] Some notable early examples of LOD rendering in 3D video games include *The Killing Cloud*, *Spyro the Dragon*, *Crash Bandicoot: Warped*, *Unreal Tournament* and *Serious Sam: The First Encounter*.
[src:level-of-detail/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] Most modern 3D games use a combination of LOD rendering techniques, using different models for large structures and distance culling for environment details like grass and trees.
[src:level-of-detail/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] The effect is sometimes still noticeable, for example when the player character flies over the virtual terrain or uses a sniper scope for long distance viewing.
[src:level-of-detail/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] Especially grass and foliage will seem to pop-up when getting closer, also known as foliage culling.
[src:level-of-detail/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] LOD can also be used to render fractal terrain in real time.
[src:level-of-detail/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] Unreal Engine 5's *Nanite* system essentially implements level-of-detail within meshes instead of just objects as a whole.
[src:level-of-detail/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] LOD is found in GIS and 3D city models as a similar concept.
[src:level-of-detail/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] It indicates how thoroughly real-world features have been mapped and how much the model adheres to its real-world counterpart.
[src:level-of-detail/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] Besides the geometric complexity, other metrics such as spatio-semantic coherence, resolution of the texture and attributes can be considered in the LOD of a model.
[src:level-of-detail/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] The standard CityGML contains one of the most prominent LOD categorizations.
[src:level-of-detail/level-of-detail-computer-graphics] The analogy of "LOD-ing" in GIS is referred to as generalization.
[src:level-of-detail/mipmap] In computer graphics, a **mipmap** (*mip* being an acronym of the Latin phrase *multum in parvo*, meaning "much in little") is a pre-calculated, optimized sequence of images, each of which has an image resolution which is a factor of two smaller than the previous.
[src:level-of-detail/mipmap] They are intended to increase rendering speed and reduce aliasing artifacts.
[src:level-of-detail/mipmap] A high-resolution mipmap image is used for high-density samples, such as for objects close to the camera; lower-resolution images are used as the object appears farther away.
[src:level-of-detail/mipmap] This is a more efficient way of downscaling a texture than sampling all texels in the original texture that would contribute to a screen pixel; it is faster to take a constant number of samples from the appropriately downfiltered textures.
[src:level-of-detail/mipmap] Since mipmaps, by definition, are pre-allocated, additional storage space is required to take advantage of them.
[src:level-of-detail/mipmap] They are also related to wavelet compression.
[src:level-of-detail/mipmap] Mipmaps are widely used in 3D computer games, flight simulators, other 3D imaging systems for texture filtering, and 2D and 3D GIS software.
[src:level-of-detail/mipmap] Mipmap textures are used in 3D scenes to decrease the time required to render a scene.
[src:level-of-detail/mipmap] They also improve image quality by reducing aliasing and Moiré patterns that occur at large viewing distances, at the cost of 33% more memory per texture.
[src:level-of-detail/mipmap] Mipmapping was invented by Lance Williams in 1983 and is described in his paper *Pyramidal parametrics*.
[src:level-of-detail/mipmap] From the abstract: "This paper advances a 'pyramidal parametric' prefiltering and sampling geometry which minimizes aliasing effects and assures continuity within and between target images." The referenced pyramid can be imagined as the set of mipmaps stacked in front of each other.
[src:level-of-detail/mipmap] The first patent issued on Mipmap and texture generation was in 1983 by Johnson Yan, Nicholas Szabo, and Lish-Yann Chen of Link Flight Simulation (Singer).
[src:level-of-detail/mipmap] Using their approach, texture could be generated and superimposed on surfaces (curvilinear and planar) of any orientation and could be done in real-time.
[src:level-of-detail/mipmap] Texture patterns could be modeled suggestive of the real world material they were intended to represent in a continuous way and free of aliasing, ultimately providing level of detail and gradual (imperceptible) detail level transitions.
[src:level-of-detail/mipmap] Texture generating became repeatable and coherent from frame to frame and remained in correct perspective and appropriate occultation.
[src:level-of-detail/mipmap] The origin of the term mipmap is an initialism of the Latin phrase *multum in parvo* ("much in little"), and map, modeled on bitmap.
[src:level-of-detail/mipmap] The term *pyramids* is still commonly used in a GIS context.
[src:level-of-detail/mipmap] In GIS software, pyramids are primarily used for speeding up rendering times.
[src:level-of-detail/mipmap] Each bitmap image of the mipmap set is a downsized duplicate of the main texture, but at a certain reduced level of detail.
[src:level-of-detail/mipmap] Rendering speed increases since the number of texture pixels (*texels*) being processed per display pixel can be much lower for similar results with the simpler mipmap textures.
[src:level-of-detail/mipmap] If using a limited number of texture samples per display pixel (as is the case with bilinear filtering) then artifacts are reduced since the mipmap images are effectively already anti-aliased.
[src:level-of-detail/mipmap] Scaling down and up is made more efficient with mipmaps as well.
[src:level-of-detail/mipmap] If the texture has a basic size of 256 by 256 pixels, then the associated mipmap set may contain a series of 8 images, each one-fourth the total area of the previous one: 128×128 pixels, 64×64, 32×32, 16×16, 8×8, 4×4, 2×2, 1×1 (a single pixel).
[src:level-of-detail/mipmap] If, for example, a scene is rendering this texture in a space of 40×40 pixels, then either a scaled-up version of the 32×32 (without trilinear interpolation) or an interpolation of the 64×64 and the 32×32 mipmaps (with trilinear interpolation) would be used.
[src:level-of-detail/mipmap] The simplest way to generate these textures is by successive averaging; however, more sophisticated algorithms (perhaps based on signal processing and Fourier transforms) can also be used.
[src:level-of-detail/mipmap] Showing each color channel of each level of an RGB mipmap as a separate plane (left) demonstrates that the whole mipmap forms a square of 4 times the area.
[src:level-of-detail/mipmap] The increase in storage space required for all of these mipmaps is a third of the original texture, because the sum of the areas 1/4 + 1/16 + 1/64 + 1/256 + ⋯ converges to 1/3.
[src:level-of-detail/mipmap] This is the inspiration for the tag *multum in parvo*.
[src:level-of-detail/mipmap] When a texture is viewed at a steep angle, the filtering should not be uniform in each direction (it should be anisotropic rather than isotropic), and a compromise resolution is required.
[src:level-of-detail/mipmap] If a higher resolution is used, the cache coherence goes down, and the aliasing is increased in one direction, but the image tends to be clearer.
[src:level-of-detail/mipmap] If a lower resolution is used, the cache coherence is improved, but the image is overly blurry.
[src:level-of-detail/mipmap] This would be a tradeoff of MIP level of detail (LOD) for aliasing vs blurriness.
[src:level-of-detail/mipmap] However anisotropic filtering attempts to resolve this trade-off by sampling a non isotropic texture footprint for each pixel rather than merely adjusting the MIP LOD.
[src:level-of-detail/mipmap] This non isotropic texture sampling requires either a more sophisticated storage scheme or a summation of more texture fetches at higher frequencies.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] In 3D computer graphics and solid modeling, a **polygon mesh** is a collection of **vertices**, **edges** and **faces** that define the shape of a polyhedral object's surface.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] It simplifies rendering, as in a wire-frame model.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] The faces usually consist of triangles (triangle mesh), quadrilaterals (quads), or other simple convex polygons (n-gons).
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] A polygonal mesh may also be more generally composed of concave polygons, or even polygons with holes.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] The study of polygon meshes is a large sub-field of computer graphics (specifically 3D computer graphics) and geometric modeling.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] Different representations of polygon meshes are used for different applications and goals.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] The variety of operations performed on meshes includes Boolean logic (Constructive solid geometry), smoothing, and simplification.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] Algorithms also exist for ray tracing, collision detection, and rigid-body dynamics with polygon meshes.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] If the mesh's edges are rendered instead of the faces, then the model becomes a wireframe model.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] Several methods exist for mesh generation, including the marching cubes algorithm.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] Volumetric meshes are distinct from polygon meshes in that they explicitly represent both the surface and interior region of a structure, while polygon meshes only explicitly represent the surface (the volume is implicit).
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] Objects created with polygon meshes must store different types of elements.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] These include vertices, edges, faces, polygons and surfaces.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] In many applications, only vertices, edges and either faces or polygons are stored.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] A renderer may support only 3-sided faces, so polygons must be constructed of many of these, as shown above.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] However, many renderers either support quads and higher-sided polygons, or are able to convert polygons to triangles on the fly, making it unnecessary to store a mesh in a triangulated form.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] A vertex in computer graphics terms is a data structure that describes the position of a point in 2, 3 or 4D space on a surface along with optional attributes - other values used to render the object correctly.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] Most attributes of a vertex represent vectors in the space to be rendered.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] These vectors are typically 2 (*x, y*) or 3 (*x, y, z*) dimensional and can include a fourth homogeneous coordinate (*w*)..
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] In real-time rendering these properties are used by a vertex shader or vertex pipeline.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] Attributes can include position, color, reflectance, specularity, texture mapping coordinates, normal vectors, and displacement mapping.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] Polygon meshes may be represented in a variety of ways, using different methods to store the vertex, edge and face data.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] Each representation has advantages and disadvantages, discussed in Smith (2006).
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] Vertex-vertex meshes represent an object as a set of vertices connected to other vertices.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] This is the simplest representation, but not widely used since the face and edge information is implicit.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] Thus, it is necessary to traverse the data in order to generate a list of faces for rendering.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] In addition, operations on edges and faces are not easily accomplished.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] However, VV meshes benefit from small storage space and efficient morphing of shape.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] The above figure shows a four-sided box as represented by a VV mesh.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] Each vertex indexes its neighboring vertices.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] The last two vertices, 8 and 9 at the top and bottom center of the "box-cylinder", have four connected vertices rather than five.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] A general system must be able to handle an arbitrary number of vertices connected to any given vertex.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] For a complete description of VV meshes see Smith (2006).
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] Face-vertex meshes represent an object as a set of faces and a set of vertices.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] This is the most widely used mesh representation, being the input typically accepted by modern graphics hardware.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] Face-vertex meshes improve on VV mesh for modelling in that they allow explicit lookup of the vertices of a face, and the faces surrounding a vertex.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] The above figure shows the "box-cylinder" example as an FV mesh.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] Vertex v5 is highlighted to show the faces that surround it.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] Notice that, in this example, every face is required to have exactly 3 vertices.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] However, this does not mean every vertex has the same number of surrounding faces.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] For rendering, the face list is usually transmitted to the GPU as a set of indices to vertices, and the vertices are sent as position/color/normal structures (in the figure, only position is given).
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] This has the benefit that changes in shape, but not geometry, can be dynamically updated by simply resending the vertex data without updating the face connectivity.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] Modelling requires easy traversal of all structures.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] With face-vertex meshes it is easy to find the vertices of a face.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] Also, the vertex list contains a list of faces connected to each vertex.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] Unlike VV meshes, both faces and vertices are explicit, so locating neighboring faces and vertices is constant time.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] However, the edges are implicit, so a search is still needed to find all the faces surrounding a given face.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] Other dynamic operations, such as splitting or merging a face, are also difficult with face-vertex meshes.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] Introduced by Baumgart in 1975, winged-edge meshes explicitly represent the vertices, faces, and edges of a mesh.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] This representation is widely used in modelling programs to provide the greatest flexibility in dynamically changing the mesh geometry, because split and merge operations can be done quickly.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] Their primary drawback is large storage requirements and increased complexity due to maintaining many indices.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] A good discussion of implementation issues of Winged-edge meshes may be found in the book *Graphics Gems II*.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] Winged-edge meshes address the issue of traversing from edge to edge, and providing an ordered set of faces around an edge.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] For any given edge, the number of outgoing edges may be arbitrary.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] To simplify this, winged-edge meshes provide only four, the nearest clockwise and counter-clockwise edges at each end.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] The other edges may be traversed incrementally.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] The information for each edge therefore resembles a butterfly, hence "winged-edge" meshes.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] The above figure shows the "box-cylinder" as a winged-edge mesh.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] The total data for an edge consists of 2 vertices (endpoints), 2 faces (on each side), and 4 edges (winged-edge).
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] Rendering of winged-edge meshes for graphics hardware requires generating a face index list, which is usually done only when the geometry changes.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] Winged-edge meshes are ideally suited for dynamic geometry, such as subdivision surfaces and interactive modelling, since changes to the mesh can occur locally.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] Traversal across the mesh, as might be needed for collision detection, can be accomplished efficiently.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] Winged-edge meshes are not the only representation which allows for dynamic changes to geometry.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] A representation which combines winged-edge meshes and face-vertex meshes is the render dynamic mesh (RDM), which explicitly stores both, the vertices of a face and faces of a vertex (like FV meshes), and the faces and vertices of an edge (like winged-edge).
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] RDM's require less storage space than standard winged-edge meshes, and can be directly rendered by graphics hardware since the face list contains an index of vertices.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] In addition, traversal from vertex to face is explicit (constant time), as is from face to vertex.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] RDM's do not require the four outgoing edges since these can be found by traversing from edge to face, then face to neighboring edge.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] RDM's benefit from the features of winged-edge meshes by allowing for geometry to be dynamically updated.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] See Tobler & Maierhofer (WSCG 2006) for more details.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] The notation *avg(V,V)* means the average number of vertices connected to a given vertex; *avg(E,V)* means the average number of edges connected to a given vertex, and *avg(F,V)* is the average number of faces connected to a given vertex.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] The notation "V → f1, f2, f3, ... → v1, v2, v3, ..." describes that a traversal across multiple elements is required to perform the operation.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] For example, to get "all vertices around a given vertex V" using the face-vertex mesh, it is necessary to first find the faces around the given vertex V using the vertex list.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] Then, from those faces, use the face list to find the vertices around them.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] Winged-edge meshes explicitly store nearly all information, and other operations always traverse to the edge first to get additional info.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] Vertex-vertex meshes are the only representation that explicitly stores the neighboring vertices of a given vertex.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] As the mesh representations become more complex (from left to right in the summary), the amount of information explicitly stored increases.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] This gives more direct, constant time, access to traversal and topology of various elements but at the cost of increased overhead and space in maintaining indices properly.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] As a general rule, face-vertex meshes are used whenever an object must be rendered on graphics hardware that does not change geometry (connectivity), but may deform or morph shape (vertex positions) such as real-time rendering of static or morphing objects.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] Winged-edge or render dynamic meshes are used when the geometry changes, such as in interactive modeling packages or for computing subdivision surfaces.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] Vertex-vertex meshes are ideal for efficient, complex changes in geometry or topology so long as hardware rendering is not of concern.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] Streaming meshes store faces in an ordered, yet independent, way so that the mesh can be transmitted in pieces.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] The order of faces may be spatial, spectral, or based on other properties of the mesh.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] Streaming meshes allow a very large mesh to be rendered even while it is still being loaded.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] Progressive meshes transmit the vertex and face data with increasing levels of detail.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] Unlike *streaming meshes*, progressive meshes give the overall shape of the entire object, but at a low level of detail.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] Additional data, new edges and faces, progressively increase the detail of the mesh.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] Normal meshes transmit progressive changes to a mesh as a set of normal displacements from a base mesh.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] With this technique, a series of textures represent the desired incremental modifications.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] Normal meshes are compact, since only a single scalar value is needed to express displacement.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] However, the technique requires a complex series of transformations to create the displacement textures.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] There exist many different file formats for storing polygon mesh data.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] Each format is most effective when used for the purpose intended by its creator.
[src:level-of-detail/polygon-mesh] Popular formats include .fbx, .dae, .obj, and .stl.
